<section>
  <title>September 12</title>

  <slide>
    <title>Using algebra to evaluate a limit</title>
    
    <p>
      Evaluate the following limits:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <me>\lim\limits_{x\to -1}\dfrac{x^2+4x+3}{x^2-1}</me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <me>\lim\limits_{x\to 4}\dfrac{x^3-4x^2}{x^3-16x}</me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      
    </p>

  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Other algebraic techniques</title>
    
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Common denominators. E.g.
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to 1}\frac{\frac1x-x}{x^2-1}
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Rationalizing. E.g.
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to 4}\frac{x^2-5x+4}{2-\sqrt{x}}
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>A trigonometric limit</title>
    
    <p>
      The limit <me>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\dfrac{\sin(2x)}{x}</me> is a <m>0/0</m> limit.
    </p>
    <p>
      Which of the following is a valid first step? 
    </p>
    <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          <p>
            Factor out the 2 to get <m>2\sin(x)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Cancel the <m>x</m> in the numerator with the <m>x</m> in the denominator
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Multiply numerator and denominator by 2
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Put your calculator in degrees mode
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>A trig limit</title>
    <p>
      Evaluate <me>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\dfrac{\sin(3x)}{2x}</me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Recall from the tutorial that <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\dfrac{\sin(x)}{x}=1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The goal here is not so much the answer as the process. (There is a wrong way to get the right answer!)
    </p>

    <p>
      If you took calc in high school: we don't get to use L'Hospital's rule.
    </p>

    <p>
      Challenge: evaluate <me>\lim\limits_{x\to 0}\frac{1-\cos(x)}{x}</me>
    </p>
  </slide>

  
  <slide>
    <title>Piecewise-defined functions</title>
    
    <p>
      Sometimes we need to work with functions that are defined differently on different parts of their domain.
    </p>

    <p>
      Applications include more than just providing examples for calculus class,
      including <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultraviolet_index">UV index</url>
      and your taxes.
    </p>

    <p>
      For the piecewise-defined function <m>f(x) = \begin{cases}2-x, \amp x\lt -1\\ 1+x^2, \amp -1\leq x\lt 2\\ \sin(\pi x),\amp x\geq 2\end{cases}</m>:
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
      <p>
        What is the value of <m>f(0)</m>?
        <ol marker="A.">
          <li>
            <p>
              2
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              0
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              1
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        What is the value of <m>f(2)</m>?
        <ol marker="A.">
          <li>
            <p>
              2
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              0
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              5
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              1
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>The absolute value is piecewise-defined</title>
    
    <p>
      You may have learned that the function <m>\abs{x}</m> measures <q>distance from 0</q>:
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>x\geq 0</m>, then <m>\abs{x}=x</m>. If <m>x\lt 0</m>, then <m>\abs{x}=-x</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Which of the following functions is equivalent to <m>f(x)=\abs{x-2}</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(x) = \begin{cases}x-2, \amp x\geq 2\\ 2-x, \amp x\lt 2\end{cases}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(x) = \begin{cases}x-2, \amp x\geq 0\\ 2-x, \amp x\lt 0\end{cases}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(x) = \begin{cases}x, \amp x\geq 2\\ -x, \amp x\lt 2\end{cases}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>

  
